cepts of property rights and argues that this period was marked by a complete disregard for previous notions of restraint on dreams of unlimited material possibility. Today, while the traditional forms of colonization that marked the Great Land Rush are no longer practiced by the European powers and their progeny in the new world, the legacy of this period can be seen in the western powers' insatiable thirst for economic growth, including newer forms of economic colonization of underdeveloped countries, and a continuing evolution of the concepts of property rights, including the development and increasing growth in importance of intellectual property rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aColonizationxHistory. 0aLand settlementxColonieszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aLand tenurexColonieszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aRight of propertyxColonieszGreat BritainxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357096240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773570962423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773570962/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles